summary: Honestly I feel like David/Niels/Skamfr  team only care about s3👀 it's the season that made the original go worldwide and it's...
question: Honestly I feel like David/Niels/Skamfr  team only care about s3👀 it's the season that made the original go worldwide and it's pretty obvious that that's what Skamfr did aim for too🤷‍♀️Fame and popularity is definitely important to them, don't say it's not because it's pretty obvious. For instant the no geoblock is a pretty huge clue lol  This is not hate just facts🤷‍♀️
answer: I disagree partly. As much as I’m hating what they did with season 4, I do believe their mistakes came from a lack of understanding how to write the POV of a character of colour more than for just lack of caring: I did support the show since the beginning. During s1/s2, the fandom was very small and the show got a lot of hate from non-french viewers for being a copy-paste of the OG. We were promised change that we never had, but you could still feel, in the way the characters were written, how the directors cared about the show and it was frankly a bit sad that they couldn’t get the recognition they deserved at the time. Now, we all know that Isak season is always the one who brings the most viewers, simply because: some LGBT watch everything with LGBT in it regardless of the previous seasons and a lot of girls fetishise gay teens (especially if they are white and conveniently beautiful). Do I think they went a little overboard with promotiing season 3 and the constant content? Yes. Do I feel that it was because of the attention they got? Yes. Can I blame them? No. They worked their asses off on a project and had seldom nothing during 2 seasons except people complaining about the lack of goid music, good acting, change and symbolism. So I can understand how s3’s success might have felt like vindication and recognition. That I can’t blame. I do wish they could have kept the same energy for Assa and Lais though, but it’s not their fault if people stopped caring the minute Elu wasn’t constantly on screen. And tbh, if them catering to Elu fans for views can make people still wamt to stick around during Imane’s season… As bad as it seems, I’m glad in a way: I care about Assa and I’m really proud of her amd her acting this season, so if they use that to put some spotlight on Assa? I’m all for that. If that can get her more jobs and recognition? I can’t blame that. But yeah, I do think that’s a little too much sometimes amd wish I could have more of just Assa and Lais interviews like we got (and still are getting) with Maxence and Axel. But well. Sometimes you have to follow the money and give your audience what they want, and as frustrated as it makes me sometimes, most of the audience only want Elu. That’s why they came for in the first place so.
